hardic Jews of Livorno, Tuscany, traded in regions near and far in the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries. Francesca Trivellato tests assumptions about ethnic and religious trading diasporas and networks of exchange and trust. Her extensive research in international archives-including a vast cache of merchants’ letters written between 1704 and 1746-reveals a more nuanced view of the business relations between Jews and non-Jews across the Mediterranean, Atlantic Europe, and the Indian Ocean than ever before. The book argues that cross-cultural trade was predicated on and generated familiarity among strangers, but could coexist easily with religious prejudice. It analyzes instances in which business cooperation among coreligionists and between strangers relied on language, customary norms, and social networks more than the progressive rise of state and legal institutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aJewish merchantszItalyzLivornoxHistoryy18th century. 0aJewszItalyzLivornoxEconomic conditionsy18th century. 0aJewszItalyzLivornoxHistoryy18th century. 0aSephardimzItalyzLivornoxEconomic conditionsy18th century. 0aSephardimzItalyzLivornoxHistoryy18th century. 0aSephardimzItalyzLivornoxSocial conditionsy18th century. 0aSephardimzItalyzLivornoxSocial life and customsxHistoryy18th century. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030013683840uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030015620140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300156201423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300156201/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY